{"cursor":"10972","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Brain injury}}\n\n\n\"'Brain damage'\" or \"Brain Injury\" (BI) is the destruction or degeneration of\nbrain cells. Brain injuries occur due to a wide range of internal and external\nfactors. A common category with the greatest number of injuries is traumatic\nbrain injury (TBI) following physical trauma or head injury from an outside\nsource, and the term acquired brain injury (ABI) is used in appropriate circles,\nto differentiate brain injuries occurring after birth, from injury due to a\ndisorder or congenital malady.\n","linknr":237,"url":"Brain_damage","recorded":1362511079,"links":28,"instances":["medical","neuropsychology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Neurotrauma","Causes of death"],"headings":["Signs and symptoms","Causes","Management","Prognosis","Body's Response to Brain Injury","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["hypoxia","medical"],["rehabilitation","neuropsychology"],["rehabilitation","neuropsychology"],["rehabilitation","neuropsychology"]],"members":["hypoxia","rehabilitation"],"related":["Brain_cells","Traumatic_brain_injury","Physical_trauma","Head_injury","Acquired_brain_injury","Birth","Genetic_disorder","Congenital_disorder","Disease","Disability","Disability","Neurocognitive_deficit","Delusion","Monothematic_delusion","Mental_retardation","Coma","Persistent_vegetative_state","Korsakoff's_Syndrome","Confabulations","Illness","Injury","Iatrogenesis","Hypoxia_(medical)","Oxygen","Poison","Teratogen","Alcohol","Infection","Neurological_illness","Chemotherapy","Stem_cells","Oligodendrocyte","Myelin","Focal_and_diffuse_brain_injury","Physical_t